  "script": "Scene 1: Establishing shot of a milkweed patch with monarchs. On-screen text: Chrysalis Stage – Transformation in Progress.\\nScene 2: A hungry caterpillar crawls along a stem and stops feeding. It wraps silk around the stem and forms a silken pad; it then molts into a chrysalis, hanging head-down in a J shape.\\nScene 3: Close-up on a green chrysalis with a thin, gold-accented ring near the top. A subtle diagram appears showing a 9–14 day timeline.\\nScene 4: Inside the chrysalis (graphics): tissues break down and reorganize into future wings, legs, antennae, and other organs.\\nScene 5: The chrysalis becomes transparent; in a moment, the butterfly emerges. Wings are soft and crumpled, then they pump blood and dry.\\nScene 6: Final shot of a newly emerged monarch perched on milkweed, ready to fly. On-screen text: This is metamorphosis at work.",
  "narration": "Welcome to the chrysalis stage of the monarch butterfly. After the caterpillar has fattened on milkweed, it anchors itself to a sturdy surface using a silk pad and, with a delicate silk girdle around its middle, hangs in a graceful J-shape. The old caterpillar skin splits, and a bright green chrysalis—often with a thin gold line along the top—hangs in place. Inside, the caterpillar’s tissues are broken down and reorganized into the future butterfly’s wings, legs, and antennae. In warm weather, this metamorphosis typically takes about 9 to 14 days, though cooler temperatures slow it down. When the chrysalis finishes, it splits open and the monarch emerges. The new butterfly pumps blood into its wings, then waits for them to dry before it can fly. The chrysalis stage is a remarkable window into transformation, reminding us how life can change in surprising, beautiful ways. Please observe from a respectful distance and never disturb the chrysalis."
